<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06258045 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06258045 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; GET OUT -- Philippine student leader BongMangahas, right, reads an &quot;eviction notice&quot; demanding that U.S. forces startto leave the country beginning Monday.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; PLANNING; CLOSING; MILITARY; FACILITY; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The United States would consider modifying a lease agreement for the Subic BayNaval Station in the central Philippines to prevent an immediate shutdown ofthe huge U.S. installation, Western diplomats said Friday.;   The diplomatssaid the Bush administration, in what appears to be a major shift in itsbargaining position, is willing to consider a three-year phased withdrawalfrom Subic instead of the 10-year base treaty that is under debate -- andfacing rejection -- in the Philippine Senate.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  U.S. REPORTEDLY WILLING TO SHORTEN SUBIC BAY LEASEFROM 10 YEARS TO 3  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The United States may also seek to delay departure from Subic for at leastseveral months, until after a proposed national referendum on the future ofthe base, the diplomats said.;   &quot;It's fair to say that we would consider anyproposal presented by the Filipinos short of an out-and-out rejection of thetreaty,&quot; a U.S. diplomat said Friday. &quot;Subic is a very valuable facility tothe United States.&quot;;   Subic Bay, the largest U.S. military base in SoutheastAsia, is a major repair and supply installation for the 7th Fleet and is hometo more than 7,000 U.S. military personnel and civilian workers.;   While itsstrategic importance has been questioned because of the end of the Cold War,U.S. officials say Subic remains a critical, and in many ways irreplaceable,component of military planning in the Pacific.;   They say Subic's functionscould be duplicated elsewhere in the region, but at a cost of several billiondollars.;   &quot;And you can't replicate those functions in any one place,&quot; said adiplomat, calling Subic &quot;a beautiful package.&quot;;   President Bush and DefenseSecretary Dick Cheney suggested this week the United States would abandonSubic before agreeing to any modification of the treaty.;   Most of the 23members of the Philippine Senate, which must ratify treaties, already haveannounced their opposition to the 10-year base agreement negotiated thissummer. Under the pact, the United States would pay $203 million a year inrent for the base.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Manila, Philippines  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910914  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  350  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, September 14, 199100258045,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>